tspan.tspan: BUTTON AND SWITCH TEMPLATES
Here are some predefined button & label combinations to
speed up the panel making process. The template will also
have links to commonly used switches and other
components
that fit these holes and button cap designs.
Many button types are constructed from a 3D printed switch
body, and a fitting button cap with the engraved text label,
cut
out of 0.8mm engraving sheet. The cap is simply
superglued on
the top of the 3D printed button.
NOTE
: These things are on several layers - bottom acrylic,
top
acrylic (panel sheets) and also the button cap engraving
layer.
Copying and pasting will keep it this way, but if you
group them,
they end up in the same layer.
TEXT AND FONTS
This template uses
Bahnschrift
font which is included in
Windows 10.
This works well for cockpit panels because it is very clear
and
readable, has good legibility also when engraved, and it
resembles closely the fonts that are being used in cockpits.
Airbus uses a very similar font, but some Boeing panels
(though not all) use
Futura
which is not freely available, so
sadly we cannot include it in this template.
Panel templates for flight simulator projects
These panel templates lets you quickly design consistent simulated aircraft cockpit
panels
using a CO2 laser cutter or CNC router and acrylic sheets. Combined with
electronic circuit
board designs it is possible to build affordable flight simulator add-on-
panels for both
entertainment and training purposes. The designs utilize MobiFlight, free
and open source
software that utilizes common Arduino boards and lets you connect
functional buttons, leds
and switches to flight simulator software.
These panels use the DZUS mounting rail spacing for holes and panel sizes, but contain
M4
sized holes for screws for practical reasons.
These panels consist of two layers: bottom clear acrylic sheet, and top white acrylic sheet.
There is also a paint mask template for the lower layer (since the edges and mounting
hole
areas need to be painted, but the center needs to be transparent so that the
backlighting can
shine through. Those blue lines frame the inner clear area, thus you can
cover the lower
panel completely with painters tape, vector cut the tape and remove the
center area.
If you use K40 Whisperer to do the laser cutting, you can export a particular layer for
cutting
by hiding all other layers before saving; K40 Whisperer only loads the visible layer.
